# 🐧 Linux

## Definition

Linux is a free and open-source operating system that manages computer hardware and software. It acts as a bridge between the user and the computer.

---

## Why is Linux Used?

- Free and open source
- Secure
- Fast
- Stable
- Reliable
- Easy to customize
- Supports multiple users
- Used for servers and cloud computing

---

## Uses of Linux

- Web Servers
- Cloud Computing
- DevOps
- Software Development
- Cybersecurity
- Android Operating System
- Embedded Systems
- Supercomputers

---

## Advantages

- Free to use
- Open source
- High security
- Better performance
- Stable
- Lightweight
- Multi-user
- Multitasking

---

## Disadvantages

- Learning curve for beginners
- Some software is not available
- Limited gaming support

---

## Key Points

- Linux is an Operating System.
- Developed in 1991.
- Created by Linus Torvalds.
- Mostly used on servers.
- Popular in DevOps and Cloud Computing.

# Show current directory
pwd

# List files and folders
ls

# List detailed files
ls -l

# List hidden files
ls -a

# List all files with details
ls -la

# Go to home directory
cd ~

# Create a folder
mkdir Linux

# Move into the folder
cd Linux

# Check current directory
pwd

# Create a file
touch file1.txt

# Create multiple files
touch file2.txt file3.txt

# List files
ls

# Open and display a file
cat file1.txt

# Write text into a file (overwrites existing content)
echo "Hello Linux" > file1.txt

# Display the file
cat file1.txt

# Add more text to the file
echo "Welcome to DevOps" >> file1.txt

# Display the updated file
cat file1.txt

# Copy a file
cp file1.txt copy.txt

# Rename a file
mv copy.txt newfile.txt

# Create another folder
mkdir Backup

# Move a file into the folder
mv newfile.txt Backup/

# Copy a folder
cp -r Backup Backup_Copy

# Display the first 10 lines of a file
head file1.txt

# Display the last 10 lines of a file
tail file1.txt

# Search for a word inside a file
grep "Linux" file1.txt

# Find a file
find . -name "file1.txt"

# Show disk usage
df -h

# Show folder size
du -sh .

# Show memory usage
free -h

# Show current user
whoami

# Show logged-in users
who

# Show user information
id

# Show running processes
ps

# Show all running processes
ps -ef

# Show live system processes
top

# Show IP address
ip a

# Test internet connectivity
ping google.com

# Stop the ping command
# Press Ctrl + C

